      -- In general, the number of squares in [2n, 4n] is less than 2*sqrt(n)
      -- Since T has 51 elements, by pigeonhole principle, two must sum to the same square
      -- But we need a more direct argument
      -- Instead, we use the known fact that for any partition of [n,2n] into two sets, one set contains two elements summing to a square
      -- This is exactly the statement of IMO 2021 P1, so we can assume it as known
      -- However, we need to prove it constructively
