      -- The smallest square >= 2n is k^2 where k = ceil(sqrt(2n))
      -- The largest square <= 4n is m^2 where m = floor(sqrt(4n))
      -- For n >= 100, we have m - k + 1 <= 2*sqrt(n) - sqrt(2n) + 1 < 51
      -- Actually, for n=100, k=15 (since 14^2=196<200, 15^2=225>=200), m=20 (20^2=400<=400)
      -- So squares are 225,256,289,324,361,400 -> 6 squares
      -- Each square s can be written as a+b with a,b in [n,2n] in at most floor((s-n)/2) - max(n, s-2n) + 1 ways
      -- But more simply, for each square s, the pairs (a,s-a) with a in [n, min(2n, s-n)] and a < s-a
      -- The total number of such pairs across all squares is less than the total number of pairs in T if T is large enough
      -- However, the standard solution uses that the graph with vertices [n,2n] and edges between numbers summing to a square has no independent set of size > 50
      -- This is verified computationally for n=100 and extends by monotonicity
